{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476203"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13698"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13698"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.06,0.38,0.16,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110863"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6314"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93033"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110863"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of cough, fever, and difficulty breathing. He has a history of cerebral palsy and is fed via a nasogastric tube. His parent reports that he had a choking episode during a feed three days ago. His medications include baclofen for spasticity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Auscultation of the chest reveals decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right upper lobe. A chest X-ray shows a right upper lobe infiltrate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial antibiotic therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin","Cefuroxime","Amoxicillin and metronidazole","Ceftriaxone","Amoxicillin-clavulanate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child with cerebral palsy presents with moderate-severity community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) following a witnessed aspiration event. The clinical features of fever, tachypnoea, tachycardia, hypoxaemia, and radiographic infiltrate confirm the diagnosis. Despite the history of aspiration, standard CAP therapy remains appropriate as most pneumonia cases, including aspiration pneumonia, result from aspiration of oropharyngeal bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial antibiotic choice. It provides excellent coverage against \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, the most common bacterial cause of CAP, and has adequate activity against many oral flora that may be aspirated. Oral therapy achieves equivalent outcomes to parenteral therapy for moderate-severity CAP in children. The liquid formulation can be easily administered through the child\u0027s existing nasogastric tube, avoiding the need for intravenous access whilst maintaining therapeutic efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefuroxime\u003C/strong\u003E is an oral second-generation cephalosporin reserved for children with immediate nonsevere or delayed nonsevere hypersensitivity to penicillins. While it provides good coverage against common respiratory pathogens, it is not first-line therapy in children who can tolerate penicillins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is a parenteral antibiotic reserved for children with severe pneumonia or those unable to tolerate oral therapy. Given that this child has moderate-severity disease and can take oral medications via his nasogastric tube, ceftriaxone is unnecessarily broad and invasive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E combination therapy provides enhanced anaerobic coverage but is not routinely required for aspiration pneumonia in moderate-severity cases. Standard CAP therapy with amoxicillin alone provides adequate coverage for most oral anaerobes. This combination would be reserved for high-severity or life-threatening disease, or for patients who have not improved after 48 hours of standard therapy with evidence suggesting anaerobic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E provides broader coverage including beta-lactamase-producing organisms and enhanced anaerobic activity. However, this broader spectrum is not routinely required for aspiration pneumonia unless the patient has high-severity or life-threatening disease. It may be considered if the patient fails to improve after 48 hours of standard therapy, anaerobic infection is suspected, and single-agent therapy is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of pneumonia, including aspiration pneumonia, develop from aspiration of oropharyngeal bacteria, and standard community-acquired pneumonia therapy provides adequate coverage.","Oral amoxicillin is as effective as parenteral therapy for moderate-severity community-acquired pneumonia in children.","Broader anaerobic coverage is not routinely required for aspiration pneumonia unless the patient has high-severity or life-threatening disease."],"references":["de Oliveira GA, Pessanha LB, Guerra LF, Martins DL, Rondina RG, Silva JR. Aspiration pneumonia in children: an iconographic essay. Radiol Bras. 2015 Nov-Dec;48(6):391-5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4725401/","Pediatric aspiration pneumonia. In: Paediatric Imaging [Online]. [Cited 2024 May]. Available at: https://pediatricimaging.org/diseases/aspiration-pneumonia/","Therapeutic Guidelines: Antibiotics. Aspiration pneumonia. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2010."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93033"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13698"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93033"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-04T18:34:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-04T18:34:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6314"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110863"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"att